---
title: Accordion / FAQ
description: Expandable content panels using the `&lt;details&gt;` and `&lt;summary&gt;` elements.
slug: accordion
cssFile: accordion.css
explanation: The <code>&lt;details&gt;</code> element has built-in open/closed state managed by the browser. The <code>open</code> attribute is added/removed natively — no JavaScript. CSS targets <code>details[open]</code> to style the expanded state and animates the + icon with a rotate <code>transform</code>.
---
{% extends "example.njk" %}
{% block demo %}
<details open>
	<summary>What is Pure CSS?</summary>
	<div class="accordion-body">Pure CSS refers to techniques that achieve interactive UI patterns using only CSS — no JavaScript required.</div>
</details>
<details>
	<summary>Which browsers are supported?</summary>
	<div class="accordion-body">All modern browsers support the features used in these examples. Check caniuse.com for specific properties.</div>
</details>
<details>
	<summary>Can I use these in production?</summary>
	<div class="accordion-body">Yes! These are real CSS techniques used in production sites. Always consider accessibility requirements for your use case.</div>
</details>
{% endblock %}

{% block html_code %}
{%- highlight "html" %}
<details>
  <summary>Question here?</summary>
  <div class="accordion-body">Answer here.</div>
</details>
{%- endhighlight %}
{% endblock %}

{% block css_code %}
{%- highlight "css" %}
details {
  border: 1px solid #e2e2e8;
  border-radius: 8px;
  margin-bottom: .5rem;
}

summary {
  padding: .9rem 1.1rem;
  font-weight: 600;
  cursor: pointer;
  list-style: none;
  display: flex;
  justify-content: space-between;
}

summary::after {
  content: "+";
  transition: transform .25s;
}

details[open] summary::after {
  transform: rotate(45deg);
}

.accordion-body {
  padding: 1rem 1.1rem;
  border-top: 1px solid #e2e2e8;
}
{%- endhighlight %}
{% endblock %}
